    "treatments": "The treatment of Acute Coronary Syndrome focuses on relieving symptoms, restoring blood flow, and preventing future events. Immediate treatment options include administering oxygen therapy, nitroglycerin to relieve chest pain, and antiplatelet medications such as aspirin to prevent further clotting. In many cases, more invasive procedures are required, such as percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI), also known as angioplasty, which involves using a balloon to open blocked arteries, often followed by the placement of a stent. For patients with more severe blockages, coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG) may be necessary. Long-term management typically includes lifestyle changes (diet, exercise, quitting smoking), medications like beta-blockers, ACE inhibitors, and statins to manage blood pressure and cholesterol, and regular follow-up with a healthcare provider to monitor heart health."
